By adding different concentrations of IAA (0.05–500 μM) into PS-CDs solutions, the intensity of as-prepared PS-CDs was measured at 530 nm wavelength, revealing the emission intensity is inversely proportional to the concentration of IAA as illustrated in Fig. 5
                        a. Importantly, the green fluorescence of PS-CDs solutions was gradually disappeared with increasing IAA concentration upon the illuminations under 365 nm of UV lamp (Fig. Sb). Calibration graph was plotted for emission intensity (Io/I) against the concentration of IAA (Fig. S12 of Supporting Information). It also suggests that the intensity of PS-CDs (Io/I) at 530 nm decreased in propositional to the concentration of IAA. From the linear regression, the correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) was found to be 0.9932, where I is emission intensity with IAA and I0
                         is emission intensity without IAA. The probe shows a wider linear range of 0.05–2.5 µM with an impressive LOD of 0.0421 µM for IAA. The developed PS-CDs-based fluorescence approach was compared with the reported other analytical techniques for IAA assay, showing superior analytical features as compared to reported methods [54–60] (Table 1
                        ).
